DESCRIPTION:This seminar will focus on classic anthropological studies of Buddhism to consider how this discipline has contributed to the larger field of Buddhist studies. We will read and discuss ethnographies of modern Buddhist communities, paying particular attention to the theoretical concerns and methodological practices that shape these works. By considering the ways these ethnographies attend to particular topics such as ritual, material culture, vernacular languages, gender, and economics, this seminar will reflect on broader changes in the study of Buddhism. Over the course of the semester, students will develop research projects on anthropological material related to their dissertation interests.
